To create a http connection with cloud server to transmit or receive data:

Library: HTTP.Client
#include <HTTPClient.h>

->to configure esp32 with the web address we want to communicate with:
http.begin(WiFiClient, "http://your-server.com/api")
For more secure connection with https:-
http.begin(WiFiClientSecure, "https://your-server.com/api")
http.begin() will return a bool value: true if intitalisation format is correct and false if URL format is wrong.

-> http.end():
 Closes the current network connection and releases all memory allocated by the HTTP client back to the ESP32 system.
It returns nothing

-> http.setTimeout():
What it does: Sets the maximum time (in milliseconds) the ESP32 will wait for the cloud server to respond to a request before giving up.
Syntax: http.setTimeout(10000) (Sets a 10-second timeout window)
Returns: Nothing (void).

->http.addHeader():
To add the header :- most general header calls-
1) http.addHeader ("Content-Type", "applicatioin/json")
Tells server what format your data is in
Without this, the server will not know how to parse the data that we put in .
"application/json" — JSON data
"application/x-www-form-urlencoded" — Form data
"text/plain" — Plain text
"text/xml" — XML data

2) http.addHeader("Authorization","Bearer <api_token");
For Aunthenticated API, where token is necessary.

3) http.addHeader("accept", "application/json");
 Tells server what format you want in response

We can have musltiple headers in single code, each one serving one purpose.
